  "text": "<html>\r\n    <head>\r\n    <style>\r\n        .unselectable {\r\n          -webkit-user-select: none;\r\n          -webkit-touch-callout: none;\r\n          -moz-user-select: none;\r\n          -ms-user-select: none;\r\n          user-select: none;\r\n        }\r\n      <\/style>\r\n      <\/head>\r\n\r\n<body class=\"unselectable\">\r\n\r\n \r\n    \r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">RATIO, PROPORTION AND RATE<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_uxqhy7xulfhs\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Ratio<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Suppose two books cost $80 and $60 dollars each. We say that the ratio of their prices is 60:80. We can reduce this ratio to the least term and the final ratio becomes 3:4. Ratios are simply fractions but that&#39;s not all. The term ratio itself means &quot;to share&quot; and that&#39;s what ratios are good for. We will use ratios to solve problems involving sharing and similar problems.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q1: Two boys share 35 mangoes in the ratio 2:3. How many mangoes does each boy get?<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">If we call the two boys A and B, then for every 2 mangoes A gets, B receives 3 mangoes. If A gets 4, B picks 6 and so on. Since the mangoes are 35 in all, we want to share those mangoes some n times, with A and B picking 2 and 3 mangoes respectively each time.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">n(2+3)=35<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">5n=35<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. n=7<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">So, A and B share the mangoes 7 times, with each boy receiving:<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A=7&times;2=<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">14 mangoes<\/span><\/u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;and<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B=7&times;3=<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">21 mangoes<\/span><\/u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;respectively.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q2: Three kids share some sweets. The first child received a third of the sweets and the second two-thirds of the remainder. If the third child gets the remaining 10 sweets, how many sweets altogether did they share?<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Let the kids be A, B and C. If they shared a total of x sweets,<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A received \u2153 x with<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">x - \u2153 x = \u2154 x remaining.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B took \u2154 of the remainder=\u2154 &times; \u2154 x = 4\/9 x with x - 4\/9x = 5\/9x left.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C took the remaining 10 sweets. Since only 5\/9x was left, we conclude that:<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">5\/9 x=10<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">5x=9&times;10=90<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">x=90\/5=<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">18 sweets in all.<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_lwkyuml7xcvd\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Proportion<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Proportion relates different magnitudes based on a given parameter. If one man gets $10 dollars, then it&#39;s only fair and proportional that two men receive twice the $10 dollars. What any number of people receive must be equal or proportional to their number and that&#39;s what proportions are good for. They &quot;compare&quot; between things to determine the exact amount that is due to the things that are compared.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q1: If 4 watches cost &euro;96, find the cost of 9 watches.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">If 4 watches cost &euro;96, then a single watch costs 96\/4=&euro;24.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. 9 watches cost 9&times;24=<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">&euro;216<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q2: How many $50-dollar books can you buy with $2000?<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Each book costs $50. Since you have $2000, you can only buy as many books as there are $50 in $2000. We have:<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">2000\/50=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">40 books.&nbsp;<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q3: If one dollar is equivalent to 360 naira whereas one-pound sterling trades for 440 naira. What is the equivalent of &pound;10 in $(dollars)?<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">$1=#360 and &pound;1=#440.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">To find how many dollars is equivalent to a pound, we check how many #360 that you can find in #440 ie since #360 represents a dollar, how many<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">of it (#360) can you find in a pound (#440).<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">ie &pound;1= 440\/360 = $1.22.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Since &pound;1 is equivalent to $1.22<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. &pound;10= 10&times;1.22=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">$12 dollars<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_z9rswzg6crcl\"><\/a><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Rate<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Rate refers to the pace at which something can be done. Two men who finish a job in 2 hours work at a different rate than others who do the same job in 1 day. We will illustrate how we can use rates and our previous knowledge of proportions to solve similar problems.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q1:&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A pump P can fill a water tank in 5h. With a second pump Q also operating, the tank can be filled in 2h. In how many hours will pump Q fill the same tank operating alone?<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">P can fill the tank in 5h. :. in 1h, P fills&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Cambria Math';\">\u2155<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;of the tank.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">P and Q fill the tank in 2h. :. in 1h, both P and Q fill &frac12; of the tank.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This means Q alone fills &frac12; -&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Cambria Math';\">\u2155<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;= 3\/10<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">of the tank in 1h.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">If Q fills 3\/10 of the tank in 1h, :. Q fills 1\/10 of the tank in 1\/3h.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Finally, since Q can fill 1\/10 of the tank in \u2153h, Q alone will fill 10\/10 of the tank in 10&times; \u2153 =&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">10\/3h<\/span><\/u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q2: A cyclist takes 3h 41mins to cycle a village travelling at 19km\/h. If he travels the next day and takes 26mins more, what was his average speed?<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This problem concerns rate but anybody that knows what speed is all about from Physics can easily answer this question. The trick is to find the total distance that the cyclist travelled from the first statement. Then we can determine his average speed given the time he travelled the village from the last sentence.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Voyage 1<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Travels Ih(60 mins)-19km (average speed 19km\/h)<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. in 1min, he cycles 19\/60km.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Since he cycled 3h(60mins) +41mins= 101mins, he covered 101&times;19\/60= 32km.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This is the distance that he travelled.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Voyage 2<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This time, he travelled 101+26=127mins= 1+7\/60= 1.167h.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">average speed = distance\/time<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. v= 32\/1.167=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">28.7km\/h<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Q3: If 5 robots can cap the entire factory beverages in 14 days, how long would 7 robots require to do the same job?<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Solution<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">5 robots can do the job in 14 days.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This means each robot does&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Cambria Math';\">\u2155<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;of the job in 14days.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">7 robots working together wil therefore do 7\/5 of the work in 14 days.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This also implies that all 7 bots do&nbsp;<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Cambria Math';\">\u2155<\/span><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;of the job in 14\/7= 2 days.<\/span><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">:. the bots do 5\/5 (whole job) in 5&times;2=&nbsp;<\/span><u><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman'; color:#0000ff;\">10 days.<\/span><\/u><\/p>\r\n    <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:200%; font-size:11pt;\"><a name=\"_y4np2mermwe6\"><\/a><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">While we cannot claim to have exhausted every possible problem on this topic, we have carefully outlined the basic methods and approaches to take while solving these kinds of problems.&nbsp;<\/span><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It&#39;s not how many problems you solve. It&#39;s rather how many you solve correctly.<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;Once you understand the approach, you are guaranteed to trash every problem that will relate to this topic.<\/span><\/p>\r\n<\/body>\r\n\r\n<\/html>",
  "chapIndex": "RATIO, PROPORTION AND RATE"
}